    {
      "title": "Pure vowels — monophthongs",
      "html": "<p>A <b>pure vowel</b> (or <b>monophthong</b>) is a vowel sound whose quality does not change during production. Received Pronunciation (RP) English has 12 pure vowels, divided into <b>short</b> and <b>long</b>.</p>\n      <h4>Short vowels (7)</h4>\n      <ul>\n        <li>/ɪ/ as in <i>bit, ship, live</i>.</li>\n        <li>/e/ as in <i>bed, said, head</i>.</li>\n        <li>/æ/ as in <i>cat, sad, hand</i>.</li>\n        <li>/ʌ/ as in <i>cup, love, done</i>.</li>\n        <li>/ɒ/ as in <i>hot, dog, want</i>.</li>\n        <li>/ʊ/ as in <i>put, foot, could</i>.</li>\n        <li>/ə/ (schwa) as in the <i>a</i> of <i>about</i>.</li>\n      </ul>\n      <h4>Long vowels (5)</h4>\n      <ul>\n        <li>/iː/ as in <i>see, meat, key</i>.</li>\n        <li>/ɑː/ as in <i>car, father, arm</i>.</li>\n        <li>/ɔː/ as in <i>saw, port, more</i>.</li>\n        <li>/uː/ as in <i>boot, soup, blue</i>.</li>\n        <li>/ɜː/ as in <i>bird, learn, work</i>.</li>\n      </ul>\n      <p>The two dots (ː) mark <b>length</b>. In an examination, expect to be asked to pick the word whose vowel matches a given symbol or another word.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Which word has the same vowel as <i>ship</i> /ɪ/? <i>seat, sheep, sit, seed</i>",
          "a": "<b>sit</b> — the others are /iː/."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Consonants — voiced and voiceless pairs",
      "html": "<p>English has 24 consonant sounds. Many come in <b>pairs</b>: one <b>voiceless</b> (vocal cords do not vibrate) and one <b>voiced</b> (vocal cords vibrate). Test by placing a finger on the throat — you feel the buzz on voiced sounds.</p>\n      <table style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse\"><tr><th style=\"text-align:left;padding:4px 8px\">Voiceless</th><th style=\"padding:4px 8px\">Voiced</th><th style=\"padding:4px 8px\">Examples</th></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"padding:4px 8px\">/p/</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">/b/</td><td>pat / bat</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"padding:4px 8px\">/t/</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">/d/</td><td>tin / din</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"padding:4px 8px\">/k/</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">/g/</td><td>coat / goat</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"padding:4px 8px\">/f/</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">/v/</td><td>fan / van</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"padding:4px 8px\">/θ/</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">/ð/</td><td>thin / this</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"padding:4px 8px\">/s/</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">/z/</td><td>sip / zip</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"padding:4px 8px\">/ʃ/</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">/ʒ/</td><td>ship / measure</td></tr>\n      <tr><td style=\"padding:4px 8px\">/tʃ/</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">/dʒ/</td><td>chin / gin</td></tr></table>\n      <p>The remaining consonants /m, n, ŋ, l, r, w, j, h/ are voiced (except /h/, which is voiceless).</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Give the voiced partner of /p/, /t/ and /f/.",
          "a": "/b/, /d/, /v/."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Word stress in two-syllable words",
      "html": "<p>Every English word of more than one syllable has one syllable pronounced more strongly — that is the <b>stressed</b> syllable. Marking is with an apostrophe before the stressed syllable, e.g. <i>'ta-ble</i>.</p>\n      <h4>General rules for two-syllable words</h4>\n      <ul>\n        <li>Most two-syllable <b>nouns and adjectives</b> are stressed on the <b>first</b> syllable: <i>'happy, 'table, 'father, 'yellow, 'silver</i>.</li>\n        <li>Most two-syllable <b>verbs</b> are stressed on the <b>second</b> syllable: <i>be'gin, re'ceive, en'joy, for'get, pre'pare</i>.</li>\n        <li>Some words change meaning by shift of stress — <b>noun/adjective</b> (first) vs <b>verb</b> (second):\n          <ul><li><i>'record</i> (noun) / <i>re'cord</i> (verb)</li>\n              <li><i>'present</i> (noun/adj) / <i>pre'sent</i> (verb)</li>\n              <li><i>'object</i> (noun) / <i>ob'ject</i> (verb)</li>\n              <li><i>'suspect</i> (noun) / <i>sus'pect</i> (verb)</li></ul>\n        </li>\n      </ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Mark the stress: <i>begin, table, receive, silver</i>.",
          "a": "<i>be'gin, 'ta-ble, re'ceive, 'sil-ver</i>."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
